<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-03-12T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-03-12T05:00:00-05:00" n="440" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d440">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">762.63/523: Telegram</note>
                    <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Czechoslovakia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Carr</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                            the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Praha</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-03-12T11:00:00+01:00">March 12, 1938—11
                            a.m.</date><lb/>[Received March 12—8:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>26. Entry German troops into Austria last night preceded by Schuschnigg
                        resignation and Seyss-Inquart’s radio broadcast urging non-resistance
                        produced profound impression here. Cabinet convened at 9 and continued into
                        the night. German allegation regarding <pb facs="0433" n="425" xml:id="pg_425"/> movement of Czech troops to Austrian border and
                        smuggling of arms from Czechoslovakia officially denied here. City appears
                        externally normal but people very tense and anxious.</p>
                    <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Carr</hi></signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>